<TITLE> Stocks soar to new high </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 2 (bdnews24.com)  Stocks closed to new highs Tuesday, as bank, mutual fund and financial heavyweights rallied amid a buying spree on anticipation of future gains. Trust Bank led the rally. "It's a sequence of the previous day. Buying pressure mainly from institutional investors has encouraged the market to rise," said Salahuddin Ahmed Khan, chief executive of Dhaka Stock Exchange. Market grew in the opening spell, steadied in the second session but finished upbeat. It was a third-day gain after stocks witnessed a sluggish trend the previous week. IT and multinational shares ascended but power, pharmaceuticals, cement stocks ended mixed. Trust Bank rallied 7.65 percent to Tk 914.25, buoyed by its growth prospects although its earning per share in the January to June period was Tk 17.6. Its reserves, according to Dhaka Stock Exchange figures, were Tk 454.26 million. Trust Bank debuted on the bourse the previous day with a face value of Tk 100, including a premium of Tk 50 each share. "Trust Bank has brought life to the market after a sluggish trend," said Moin AL Kashem, an analyst. Anwarul Kabir Bhuiyan, executive director of Securities and Exchange Commission and also the chief of surveillance, put the market uptrend down to buying interests. "It's a reflection of availability of surplus funds in the market. It requires increase in the supply of issues to absorb these funds," he said. AB Bank, which claimed to have earned Tk 134.13 each share in the six months to June, surged 6.93 percent to close at an all-time high of Tk 2630.75. Speculation of attractive dividend drove AIMS 1st Mutual Fund, one of the biggest funds, 11.06 percent higher to finish at a record Tk 8.73. BRAC Bank ended higher for a third day, rising 0.90 percent to Tk 1309 on reports of allotment of redeemable preference shares of Tk 100 million to Trust Bank. It had secured the SEC's nod to issue Tk 500 million bond through private placement. Summit Power, the most active issue in the power sector, slipped 1.13 percent to Tk 1440.50. The DGEN or general index closed at an all-time high of 2647.51, up 20.48 points or 0.77 percent. The DSI or all-share price index was up 23.28 points or 1.07 percent to 2191.72. The DSE-20 blue chip index added 11.04 points or 0.54 percent to 2032.29. A total of 116 scrips advanced, 69 dropped and 16 held steady. Turnover declined to Tk 2.09 billion from trading of 2, 26, 10, 340 shares. All the major indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also gained. Some 78 issues rose, 35 declined and five remained stable with 37, 86, 000 shares worth Tk 296.55 million traded. bd
